https://prez.dev/description.@value: Methods used to spatially locate geological features and exploration, mining and related infrastructure sites. These can be either features directly observed in the field (e.g. site/outcrop descriptions, structural readings, etc.) or obtained from legacy and current documents/datasets (e.g. airphotos, maps, previously published reports, exploration reports, etc.). Each location method has a spatial accuracy that indicates an estimate of the approximate error in the location. Captured geographical locations for geological or mining features are expressed as a set of coordinates (latitude and longitude degrees), with or without an elevation above or below sea level.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Geographical location based on Geoscience Australia (GA) Common Earth Model, a unified representation of Australia's geology that allows users to explore geological aspects of an area in detail. Accuracy estimated to be around 100 m.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hist.@value: Geoscience Australia's Common Earth Model is a collection of data compiled from various sources that aims to give a unified overview of the geology of Australia. The data are visualised in the Geoscience Australia 3D Data Viewer software, enabling users to interactively explore and analyze the geological features and formations of different locations across Australia.
